<HEADLINE>
FT  21 FEB 92 / London Stock Exchange: Equity Futures and Options Trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE and JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A BRIGHT start to the stock index futures was soon reversed by disappointing
corporate results and volatile trading, write Christopher Price and Joel
Kibazo.
The March contract opened strongly at 2,564 on the back of a firm Wall
Street overnight and improved performance by Tokyo; by 9am it had moved
swiftly to its high point of the day of 2,572. However, figures from Shell
Transport knocked March sharply, and it reached a low point for the day of
2,545 by 11am.
Positive sentiment from the other European bourses began to rub off on the
London market after midday and the FT-SE futures commenced a slow recovery.
In spite of a lacklustre start, Wall Street picked up and March followed
suit, ending the day at 2,564, up 14 on the previous session and some 11
points above its estimated fair value premium to cash of about 10. Turnover
reached 6,422 contracts.
In the LTOM, traders reported a 'directionless' session with turnover coming
to 23,112 contracts. The FT-SE Index option traded 6,624 lots. Glaxo was the
busiest stock option on 4,330 contracts dealt, with the March 600 calls the
most active series. This was followed by BTR with a day's total of 2,678
lots.
