FT  21 FEB 92 / International Company News: Harley-Davidson shares leap
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Harley-Davidson, the only US motorcycle manufacturer, soared
yesterday after the company turned in a 22 per cent increase in
fourth-quarter sales.
Although Harley's fourth-quarter operating profits slid 2 per cent to
Dollars 13m from Dollars 13.2m in 1990, lower interest and other expenses
helped the company's underlying pre-tax earnings soar 289 per cent to
Dollars 10.7m from Dollars 3.7m.
Net income in the 1991 fourth quarter was Dollars 7.3m, or 41 cents a share,
on sales of Dollars 237.7m, against earnings of Dollars 3.9m, or 22 cents,
on sales of Dollars 194.3m a year earlier. Motorcycle and related product
sales surged 29 per cent in the 1991 quarter.
On Wall Street, Harley's stock added Dollars 5 1/4 to close at Dollars 53
1/2 .
Harley, the sole survivor of the 143 US companies which once made
motorcycles, has overcome Japanese competition to regain the top spot in the
big motorcycle market. It now commands about 61 per cent of the 850cc class.
Harley shipped 68,626 motorcycles in 1991, up 10 per cent from 1990, with
most of the growth coming in the fourth quarter when they climbed 31 per
cent to 18,839.
For the whole of 1991, operating profits fell 18 per cent to Dollars 68.6m
from Dollars 83.4m, while earnings before tax and extraordinary items slowed
to Dollars 58.1m from Dollars 62.6m.
Net income for the year was Dollars 37m, or Dollars 2.08, against Dollars
37.8m, or Dollars 2.12. Sales grew 9 per cent to Dollars 939.9m from Dollars
864.6m.
Mr Ronald Glantz, an analyst at Dean Witter Reynolds, was disappointed by
Harley's flat underlying fourth-quarter earnings on strong sales, but he
remained bullish about Harley's prospects. 'What other consumer durable
company is making money and apologising to dealers for not being able to
meet demand?' he said.
In the 1991 quarter, Holiday Rambler sales rose 19 per cent to Dollars 51m.
The improvement, however, was led by lower margin vehicles and the business
suffered a greater operating loss of Dollars 6.9m, against Dollars 1.9m in
the 1990 quarter.
