FT  21 FEB 92 / Liquidator traces Maxwell pension cash
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LIQUIDATORS have so far recovered only Pounds 237m of the Pounds 695m
pension fund assets held by Bishopsgate Investment Management, from which
the late Mr Robert Maxwell took money in an effort to save his crumbling
business empire.
Mr Neil Cooper, a partner with Robson Rhodes, who was appointed provisional
liquidator to BIM by the courts in December, said yesterday in his first
public statement since starting the investigation, that he had traced all
but Pounds 2m of the pension fund assets.
He estimated that Mr Maxwell transferred Pounds 217m from BIM to third
parties, in transactions including security against loans made by banks to
his companies. Any attempts to recover these assets over the coming months
are likely to involve a flurry of legal actions.
A further Pounds 239m was liquidated by Mr Maxwell and the balance
transferred to other companies in his group.
Any cash remaining from these transfers is now controlled by the
administrators and receivers of the businesses and Mr Cooper said it is
probably 'irrecoverable'.
He believes the value of the assets managed by BIM would now total about
Pounds 695m. The figure is lower than some previous estimates because it has
been revalued in the past few days to reflect current market values.
Mr Ken Trench, chairman of the Maxwell private companies' pension fund
members association, said: 'It's good news to realise that something is
happening, but there is still a massive black hole. There may well be some
people who never receive their pensions.'
Some Pounds 111m of the safeguarded assets belong to the Common Investment
Fund, which contained the assets of six pension funds of Maxwell companies
and should have totalled Pounds 411m.
The remaining Pounds 126m recovered belonged to pension funds in their own
names. However, Mr Cooper refused to state how the assets recovered divided
between the different pension funds.
Mr Cooper said he had informed the independent trustees of these figures.
Over the past few weeks Mr Cooper has interviewed Mr Kevin Maxwell, Mr Ian
Maxwell and Mr Larry Trachtenberg. He will interview other former directors
and senior employees of BIM over the coming months.
Pension loans, Page 23
