FT  21 FEB 92 / Scottish businesses deliver double blow to Tories
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Conservative party's hopes of securing the backing of Scottish
businesses for the preservation of the constitutional status quo in Scotland
suffered a double blow yesterday.
The Confederation of British Industry in Scotland said it now accepted that
constitutional change was inevitable and that 'the present mechanisms of
government could be improved'. But it said the alternatives on offer from
the opposition would be bad for the Scottish economy and challenged all
parties to offer better proposals.
Earlier, a cross-party group of businessmen heading medium-sized companies
launched an organisation named Business Says Yes - to constitutional change.
They said many business people were 'eagerly awaiting the establishment of
Scotland's own government' and believed it would be good for business.
Leading Scottish financial institutions on Wednesday expressed strong
misgivings about the possible effects on their business of a devolved
Scottish parliament of the kind proposed by Labour and the Liberal
Democrats. According to a trade association survey most believed it would
damage the financial sector.
The acknowledgment by the CBI in Scotland that the constitutional status quo
was no longer tenable came only 10 months after a survey showed that
three-quarters of its members were opposed to any form of Scottish assembly,
with more than half favouring no change.
Mr Alasdair MacCallum, chairman of the CBI in Scotland, said that its main
objection was to the proposal by Labour that a devolved Scottish parliament
could impose higher income tax in Scot-land than in the rest of the UK.
But independence, proposed by the Scottish National party, was the most
dangerous option of all, he said.
In Edinburgh, Mr Tom McGregor, chairman of Business Says Yes, said a
Scottish parliament would be responsive to the needs of Scottish business.
It would end the over-taxation of Scottish business caused by the fact that
business rates in Scotland are 40 per cent higher than in England.
It believes the business community would be represented in a Scottish
parliament in a way that it is not through the Conservative party, which it
sees as unpopular and out of touch in Scotland.
In the Commons yesterday Mr John Major, the prime minister, accused the
Scottish National party of 'profoundly misleading' the Scottish people in
its campaign to end the 1707 union,
He insisted: 'The union between England and Scotland is greater than the sum
of its parts and always has been.'
</TEXT>
