FT  21 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Lamont attacks 'socialist' savings
proposal - National Insurance contributions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CONSERVATIVES yesterday hit out at Labour proposals for a 9 per cent
'tax' on unearned income of more than Pounds 3,000 a year, in an assault
featuring a rare excursion from pre-Budget purdah by Mr Norman Lamont, the
chancellor.
Labour plans to extend National Insurance contributions to income from
savings of more than Pounds 30,000 held by those below retirement age. Mr
Lamont, flanked by a picture of a blood-filled mosquito that will star in a
Tory poster campaign, inveighed against what he said was an 'envy tax on
savings'.
Mr Lamont, attempting to tap a vein which has proved rewarding for the
government in recent campaigning, said: 'When it comes to tax, the Labour
party is still socialist. It has to be - that is the price of Labour's
spending plans.'
He sought to highlight the contradiction between Labour's commitment to
training and investment as an economic cure-all and its simultaneous
espousal of a policy 'which will slash investment'.
The 'worst effect' of the tax would be on the overall level of savings, said
Mr Lamont. 'Fewer people will save with a top rate of income tax of 59 per
cent on earnings and on savings.'
Mr Lamont said the proposed savings charge could hit 1.1m taxpayers and
would undermine the promise made by Mr Neil Kinnock, the Labour leader, that
nobody earning less than Pounds 21,000 a year would pay a penny more in tax
or national insurance.
Some 750,000 of those affected would be basic rate tax payers, he said.
'Many people who are not at retirement age but depend on their income from
savings would indeed be hit hard,' he said.
Mr Lamont was supported by Mr Tony Newton, social security secretary, who
portrayed the tax as a last-ditch stand against a Tory-inspired revolution
in inheritance.
The tax would take an average of Pounds 5.40 a week from 750,000 basic-rate
taxpayers and would cost a further 360,000 higher-rate taxpayers an average
of Pounds 34 a week, he said.
