<HEADLINE>
FT  21 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: in Brief
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
POLL TAX: The High Court yesterday refused to close the loophole holding up
poll tax prosecutions, ruling that liability orders based on computer
print-outs were illegal.
Declaring computer evidence 'hearsay', the court upheld an earlier ruling by
Coventry magistrates. The ruling could affect thousands of pending
debt-collection cases.
The bill introducing the council tax, currently before the Lords, will make
such evidence admissible for the future, but councils are unlikely to
proceed with liability orders affected by the ruling until the bill becomes
law early next month.
Mr Michael Portillo, local government minister, said the bill had been
amended 'precisely to make clear that in future computer evidence will not
be regarded as hearsay'.
*****
ENVIRONMENT: The government has dismissed as 'unrealistic' European
Commission plans to start an energy tax to combat global warming early next
year.
Officials giving evidence to the House of Lords' European Communities
committee yesterday said it could take five years to agree details and
introduce an EC 'carbon tax' on fossil fuels.
They also said they doubted that detailed proposals on the tax would be
ready for presentation to the Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro in June.
*****
TRANSPORT: The Transport and Works Bill failed to complete its report stage
in the Commons last night when the government chose not to extend the
sitting until consideration of the measure had been concluded.
The bill would empower the government to authorise rail, tramway and inland
waterway work schemes, replacing the need to go through the lengthy and
often costly private-bill procedure currently required.
</TEXT>
