FT  21 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Thatcher becomes 'freelance writer'
 -MPs' interests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MRS Margaret Thatcher, the former prime minister, has become a 'freelance
writer, lecturer and broadcaster', according to the latest annual register
of MPs' business interests, published yesterday.
She also records some staff to help with her lecture tours in the US and
Japan, and visits around the world.
Sir Geoffrey Howe, former deputy prime minister, is now listed as
non-executive director of BICC, the international cables and construction
group, and Glaxo Holdings, the pharmaceuticals group. He is also a special
adviser to Jones Day Reavis and Pogue (International Law Firm), and lists
occasional fees from lecturing, broadcasting and writing.
It is the first time these activities have been set out in the register, as
last year's register was published too close to the Tory leadership contest
of November 1990 for the departing protagonists to have acquired their new
interests.
Other former ministers have continued to add to their business activities.
Mr Nicholas Ridley, former trade and industry secretary, has become a
consultant to Whittingdale Holdings, the unit trust group, and Mr Nigel
Lawson, former chancellor, has joined the international advisory board of
Creditanstalt, the bank.
Apart from his brief connection with Maxwell Communication Corporation, Mr
Peter Walker, former Welsh secretary, lists new interests as a director of
the Vietnam Fund, which will invest in joint ventures with Vietnamese
companies. He is also an adviser to the Treuhandanstalt, the body for
privatising former east German companies.
Under parliamentary rules MPs have to register interests as they are
acquired, but the register itself is printed only annually. The all-party
committee responsible for the register is due to publish a report early next
month on tightening up the registration and declaration of interests.
Register of Members' Interests on 13 January 1992. HMSO. Pounds 16.60.
