<HEADLINE>
FT  21 FEB 92 / Satellite communication licences awarded
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGO DIXON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO companies were licensed yesterday to provide international satellite
communications services.
British Aerospace Communications and Alpha Lyracom, the US private satellite
operator, plan to provide a range of voice and data services by installing
satellite dishes on office roofs. They are expected to provide a new form of
competition to the international services run by BT and Mercury
Communications.
The government has awarded the licences as part of its policy of
liberalising the telecommunications market following last year's review of
the BT/Mercury duopoly.
The market for satellite communications has developed quickly in the US
where there are nearly 70,000 dishes in use, according to Comsys, a
specialist UK market research company. In Europe, however, the market has
been slow to develop because of tight regulations which are now being
relaxed.
Mr Peter Lilley, the trade and industry secretary, claimed the UK had 'gone
further than any other country in liberalising satellite networks'. He said
other applications to provide similar services would be considered on their
merits.
BAe already has similar satellite licences in France and Germany. It is also
part of a multinational consortium that plans to build and launch the
Dollars 500m (Pounds 284m) Orion satellite system in 1995. Alpha Lyracom has
satellite licences in France, Germany and the US. Its first Pan American
Satellite has been in operation for several years and several more are
planned to be launched over the next few years.
The new licences are unrestricted for data services but have one important
restriction if they are used for voice services. They will only be allowed
to connect with the public telephone network in either the UK or a foreign
country but not with both at the same time.
The government yesterday also awarded four radio-based data communications
licences. The operators, which have already been providing data services
under a more strict regime, are: Cognito, Hutchinson Mobile Data, Paknet and
Ram.
Mr Lilley said the Department of Trade and Industry had received 20 other
firm applications for telecommunications licences since the market was
liberalised last year, and 30 indications of strong interest from companies.
The DTI said there would be a 'rolling programme' under which perhaps one
new licence would be awarded every month.
The DTI also confirmed it was close to licensing a new type of international
operator to lease telecommunications capacity in bulk from BT and Mercury
and re-sell it.
