<HEADLINE>
FT  21 FEB 92 / Scheme launched to boost private share ownership
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Personal Finance Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROSHARE, an organisation committed to turning the UK into a 'nation of
shareholders', was launched yesterday with financial backing from the
Department of Trade and Industry, the Stock Exchange and 20 industrial and
commercial companies.
The new organisation will campaign for reforms such as fiscal incentives for
private equity holdings, more education of schoolchildren in personal
finance and for companies to use 'best practice' when establishing employee
share-ownership schemes.
ProShare has initial funding of Pounds 1m a year for three years.
The organisation said that in spite of the privatisations of the 1980s,
which increased the number of shareholders from 3m to 11m, the habit of
shareholding was not deeply rooted. Three quarters of private investors own
shares in no more than two companies and 54 per cent own shares in one.
Only 3 per cent of private investors own shares in 11 or more companies,
which is generally accepted to be necessary to build a diversified
portfolio.
The proportion of shares held by private individuals has fallen from 65.8
per cent to 21.3 per cent over the past 30 years.
Sir Peter Thompson, the former chairman of transport company NFC, is
ProShare's chairman. He said an increase in private share ownership would
improve the liquidity of the stock market and would have beneficial effects
on the economy by increasing the feeling of ownership among the workforce.
ProShare would try to provide private investors with improved information
and research and would encourage more user-friendly and lower-cost share
distribution services. Sir Peter said there was a lack of knowledge of share
ownership among the population and ProShare would aim to educate people in
the risks and rewards.
The organisation has letters of support from all three main political
parties. Mr John Major, the prime minister, said in a letter to Sir John
Harvey-Jones, ProShare's president: 'The aim of the new body, which we
share, is for a society whereby the fortunes of shareholders, management and
employees are successfully bound up together.'
Sir David Walker, chairman of the Securities and Investments Board, the
chief regulator for the financial services industry, said: 'We welcome the
formation of ProShare. There is a clear need for a responsible organisation
to represent the interests of private investors.'
</TEXT>
