FT  21 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): Lack of training strategy criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT-funded training suffers from a lack of a clear and coherent
long-term strategy, Astra Training Services, the biggest national provider
of craft training, has told a Commons select committee.
Astra, created in a management buy-out of 45 of the 60 skillcentres
privatised by the government in 1990, said in a written submission to the
Commons employment committee that the training market had become
under-resourced. The company also said that funders were too concerned with
the short term.
It said: 'Skill shortages are already reappearing despite the recession and
rising unemployment.'
Astra said the government's strategy was to increase the commitment of
employers and individuals to meeting their own training needs, thereby
minimising its own involvement. 'This has not happened in practice, thereby
reducing total funding available and consequently the range and quality of
training provision.'
Astra estimated that government grants covered less than 50 per cent of the
total costs of training. Increased employer contributions were difficult to
achieve because most companies were cutting jobs and found it difficult to
justify taking on extra staff.
'The prospects of increasing the placement fee to compensate for the reduced
government funding are remote during a recession,' Astra said.
The company said that the auditing procedures demanded by the government
were costly to provide and were not allowed for in funding regimes.
It said it was deeply concerned that many training providers were in
financial difficulties and were leaving the training market. 'This damage to
the training infrastructure may take years to repair,' it said.
</TEXT>
