<HEADLINE>
FT  21 FEB 92 / Shift seen in women's retirement age
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK and DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WOMEN IN occupational pension schemes which provide for them to retire at 65
for the first time outnumber those in schemes which provide for retirement
at 60, according to a survey of pension fund managers.
The survey also showed a sharp rise in schemes with equal retirement ages
for men and women.
The 1991 annual survey of the National Association of Pension Funds (NAPF),
released yesterday, showed that 42 per cent of schemes - with 51 per cent of
women in pension schemes - have a normal retirement age for women of 65.
A further 49 per cent of schemes - with 42 per cent of the women - have 60
as the retirement age for women.
Men and women have equal retirement ages in 75 per cent of schemes, compared
with 53 per cent last year. In 57 per cent of those schemes the common
retirement age is 65 and in 32 per cent it is 60.
This reflects changes in the private sector while the government is
considering the equalisation of pension ages for state pensions. The
Department of Social Security issued a consultation document on the subject
late last year.
Mr Brian MacMahon, NAPF chairman, said: 'Industry is sending a clear message
on the need to resolve the equalisation of state pension ages. The NAPF
continues to support the principle of flexible retirement with 65 as the
pivotal age.'
The survey was conducted among 778 members of the occupational pensions
industry and covered 900 pension funds. It showed that 90 per cent of those
in pension funds now receive guaranteed annual increases and a further 9 per
cent have payments reviewed annually.
For 94 per cent of those in the public sector, payments increase in line
with the retail prices index. In the private sector 45 per cent of schemes
offer limited price indexation, which is the RPI up to 5 per cent.
Annual survey of occupational pension schemes. NAPF, 12-18 Grosvenor
Gardens, London SW1W 0DH. Pounds 96.
TRADE UNION pressure for greater control on the administration of pension
funds in the wake of the Maxwell affair intensified this week as unions
submitted evidence to the Commons select committee on social security, Diane
Summers writes.
The National Communications Union, which represents 150,000 members, the
majority of whom are in two BT pension schemes, told the committee it wanted
a range of measures in recognition that 'pensions are the deferred pay of
employees'.
The NCU submission includes proposals for regulations to guide actuaries in
the assumptions they use to value surpluses. The union says there should be
rules on the provision of information to pension scheme members about
management and investment strategies.
The Trades Union Congress has already called for pension legislation to
ensure half of a trust board is taken from the scheme's membership. The TUC
wants unions and trustees to receive information at the same time as
employers.
Other unions to submit evidence to the select committee have mostly been
directly involved in the Maxwell businesses. They include the GPMU print
union, the National Union of Journalists and Balpa, the airline pilots'
union.
Maxwell pension cash, Page 21
</TEXT>
