FT  21 FEB 92 / Further action considered to recover Outhwaite losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Lloyd's Names who were not included in last week's out-of-court
settlement in the Outhwaite case are examining legal action of their own in
an attempt to recover losses.
About 150 of the Outhwaite Names received legal advice this week from the
solicitors DJ Freeman and will meet on Monday evening to consider their next
move. Names are the individuals whose assets back underwriting at Lloyd's.
Last week, 987 Names backed legal action against RHM Outhwaite and 80 other
agents on the grounds of negligence and breach of contract and won Pounds
116m in a negotiated settlement. Other Names on the syndicate - of whom most
appear to have been working Names (Names employed by Lloyd's agencies or
brokers) - opted not to join the action and do not benefit from the deal.
'The non-litigant Names felt legal action was not the way to proceed but are
now unhappy that their interests have been ignored,' said an Outhwaite Name
who has helped co-ordinate the action.
Mr David Tiplady of DJ Freeman said that because more than six years have
elapsed since Mr Outhwaite underwrote the loss-making US liability contracts
that were at the centre of the original legal case, future actions could be
'time-barred'. He has examined a number of technical arguments to circumvent
this obstacle.
Separately DJ Freeman, which represents three other groups of Names involved
in legal disputes with their agents, has dissociated itself from the
campaign by a separate firm of solicitors, Michael Freeman, to prevent
Lloyd's from drawing down Names' deposits in order to meet cash calls (to
fund anticipated insurance losses). Mr Michael Freeman issued motions for
the injunctions - which seek to prevent Lloyd's drawing down on Names
deposits - on Wednesday.
