FT  21 FEB 92 / Cambodia to get 16,000 UN troops
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The massive UN operation proposed for Cambodia under the Paris peace accords
will require 15,900 troops and 1,000 foreign civilian administrators at a
cost close to Dollars 2bn, according to an official plan released last
night, reports Michael Littlejohns from New York.
Mr Yasushi Akashi, head of the operation, called it the most ambitious
project of its kind. He voiced his belief that the Security Council would
approve a detailed blueprint prepared by Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, the
secretary general, by the end of next week.
If so, the troop build-up will begin next month, with full deployment due by
the end of May. The Cambodian operation would be the UN's biggest
peacekeeping mission since the Congo in the 1960s.
