<HEADLINE>
FT  21 FEB 92 / UN urges action to stem Iraqi brutality
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS, ROBERT MAUTHNER and MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA, LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
VIOLATIONS of human rights by the present Iraqi regime are so grave and so
widespread that few parallels can be found since the Second World War, a UN
human rights report says.
Presenting his report yesterday to the UN Human Rights Commission meeting in
Geneva, Mr Max van der Stoel, the special rapporteur for Iraq, said
exceptional measures were called for.
'Every day, Iraqi citizens are in danger of losing their lives. Scarcely a
day passes without executions or hangings. In such a situation, mere
condemnations are not enough.'
British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd warned last night that the Gulf war
allies would not 'stand idly by' while President Saddam Hussein continued to
repress Iraqis and violated UN resolutions.
He said: 'Still he cheats: UN inspectors have found huge covert programmes
for weapons of mass destruction.
'Saddam's inner circle prevent supplies from reaching the Kurdish population
in northern Iraq, or the Shia in the southern marshes. The blockade of the
North is a clear violation of the Security Council that demanded an end to
repression in Iraq.'
In his UN report Mr van der Stoel, a former Dutch foreign minister, urged
the dispatch of a team of human rights monitors to Iraq which would remain
as long as necessary. 'A resolute effort must be made to save human lives,'
he said.
The report catalogues summary executions, arbitrary detention of political
and religious opponents, enforced disappearances, and routine use of torture
to extract confessions. 'The number of victims  .. is certainly in the
hundreds of thousands,' it says.
Replying to Mr van der Stoel's remarks, Mr Mohammed Al-Douri, Iraq's chief
representative to the 53-member Human Rights Commission, said Iraq strongly
rejected the report as part of the west's propaganda campaign against the
country.
A commission established by the UN Security Council to determine
compensation payable by Iraq to victims in the invasion and occupation of
Kuwait is recommending surprisingly low ceilings - only Dollars 30,000 per
individual and Dollars 60,000 per family, Michael Littlejohns reports from
New York.
The Commission reported last night that the Iraqis want a five-year grace
period before making any payment into the UN fund to which claims will be
addressed. Officials said these were bound to run into thousands, but they
did not have a precise estimate.
In seeking a delay, Iraq said it must have time to meet its essential
domestic needs, including repairing an estimated Dollars 194bn of damage
done by the coalition forces.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 4
</PAGE>
