<HEADLINE>
FT  21 FEB 92 / 'Out-of-area' issue seen to threaten Nato
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NATO'S SURVIVAL may be at risk unless members are prepared to contemplate
the use of forces outside allied territory, at least in defence of democracy
in the countries of central and eastern Europe, a top alliance official
warned yesterday.
Mr Michael Legge, who was responsible for drawing up Nato's new strategic
doctrine, approved by all 16 members at a summit in Rome in November, said
he was disappointed at the lack of commitment on 'out-of-area' operations.
Several European members were reluctant to see allied forces employed
outside the Nato area 'in any circumstances'. But, speaking at the Royal
United Services Institute in London yesterday, he called on allies to extend
the boundaries of possible action 'at least throughout Europe'.
Failure to do so, he said, would put Nato's credibility at risk in public
opinion and undermine support for the alliance in the US. He emphasised that
any actions would not necessarily have to be under a Nato flag.
Mr Legge, a Briton, has been Nato's assistant secretary-general for defence
planning and policy since 1988. He oversaw the work on redefining the
alliance's purpose and military guidelines following its reassessment in
1990 of the threat from what was then the Warsaw Pact.
The agreed text of the alliance's new Strategic Concept acknowledged the
existence of 'risks of a wider nature' than direct threats to allies' own
territory. But it made no provision for dealing with them beyond a passing
reference to existing arrangements for consultation and co-ordination among
allies.
</TEXT>
