<HEADLINE>
FT  21 FEB 92 / Budget for expansion agreed by cabinet
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS, EMMA TUCKER and PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CABINET gave the go-ahead yesterday for an expansionary pre-election
Budget against the backdrop of the longest UK recession since the Second
World War and an opinion poll putting Labour in the lead.
Mr John Major hinted at a significant increase in public borrowing to fund
tax cuts expected in the Budget on March 10 - but collided with Mr Neil
Kinnock, Labour leader, on spending priorities in an increasingly excited
atmosphere at Westminster.
Figures from the Central Statistical Office showed non-oil output in the UK
fell for the sixth successive quarter. Mr Kinnock turned a past Tory
election slogan on the prime minister to claim: 'It's official - Majorism
isn't working.' Later he said, borrowing for tax cuts was 'a confidence
trick'.
The NOP poll for The Independent today puts Labour on 42 per cent, four
points ahead of the Tories, with the Liberal Democrats on 15 per cent. For
the first time in recent months, it also shows more voters believe the
Conservative are not competent at economic management than competent.
In the same poll last month, Labour led the Tories by 43-40.
Labour strategists said election battle lines were clearer. Voters faced a
choice between basic rate tax cuts under the Tories or more health service
spending and incentives for industry under Labour.
In the Commons, Mr Major, who has brought Mr Michael Heseltine, environment
secretary, into a campaign 'A team' on election strategy, said the
government had spent 'in excess' of the real health spending increases
promised by Labour at the 1987 election. He again insisted that a world
economic slowdown was to blame for the UK's recession.
In an interview with The Daily Telegraph this week, Mr Major said it would
be 'prudent' to increase borrowing in a recession. Last night, however, Sir
Alan Walters, economic adviser to former prime minister Mrs Margaret
Thatcher, undermined Mr Major's stance. He said on Channel Four that Mr
Nigel Lawson, former chancellor, was '70 per cent' to blame for the UK's
economic problems.
The cabinet discussed the Budget for 80 minutes, including a presentation of
forecasts by Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor. The figures for gross
domestic product exacerbated the 'mood of realism' described by Downing
Street.
Excluding oil and gas, GDP fell by 0.4 per cent in the fourth quarter of
1991 compared with the previous quarter. This brought the overall year on
year decline for 1991 to 2.5 per cent, the sharpest yearly contraction since
1931.
Downing Street acknowledged that lower-than-forecast growth would mean the
public sector borrowing requirement as a share of GDP would be 'somewhat
higher' than forecast in the Autumn Statement.
An official statement said cabinet ministers 'reaffirmed their commitment to
prudent management of the public finances'. However, a significant majority
of cabinet minsters expects a 1p cut in the basic income tax rate as the
showpiece for an April 9 election - likely to be called before the end of
Budget week.
As ministers pressed Mr Lamont to reconcile the Treasury's insistence on
fiscal prudence with the political need for tax cuts, Mr Chris Patten, the
party chairman, repeated the government's commitment to balance the Budget
'over the economic cycle'. Mr Patten refused to say whether that would imply
an obligation to wipe out the need for public borrowing during the lifetime
of the next parliament.
Mr Lamont, who emerged again from Budget purdah to join Mr Patten at a
Westminster press conference attacking Labour's tax plans, refused to answer
questions on the government's economic strategy.
Colleagues, however, said the chancellor was concerned to lower expectations
of a tax-cutting 'bonanza'.
In spite of Mr Patten's remarks, some cabinet members are convinced the
commitment to a balanced Budget will have to be dropped after the election
in order to meet pledges on spending and tax.
Mr Paddy Ashdown, Liberal Democrat leader, said there were 'more ministers
spray-painting rosy pictures than there are taking the tough action we
need'.
