<HEADLINE>
FT  21 FEB 92 / International Company News: Consortium buys Pebble Beach
golf resort
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE controversial Japanese owner of the Pebble Beach golf resort in
California, one of the most famous courses in the US, has been forced by
financial difficulties to sell out to a consortium organised by Sumitomo
Bank.
Mr Minoru Isutani, a self-made Japanese tycoon who bought the course for
around Dollars 1bn, has had to dispose of it for about Dollars 500m after
failing to complete a scheme to fund the purchase by sales of memberships to
wealthy Japanese.
Mr Isutani bought Pebble Beach in 1990 through a US subsidiary, which he
then quickly sold to US investors after the deal was concluded. Mr Isutani
is also well known for his ties with Mr Hisashi Shinto, former chairman of
Nippon Telegraph and Telephone, who was forced to resign due to his
involvement in the Recruit stock scandal.
Taiheiyo Club, a golf course developer, has joined Sumitomo Credit Service,
the credit card company under Sumitomo Bank, to buy Pebble Beach - which
will be the site of the US Open golf tournament this year - from Mr Isutani.
Mr Isutani's close ties with Itoman, the Osaka-based trading company facing
financial restructuring due to its involvement in real-estate-related
speculation, prompted Sumitomo Bank, under which Itoman is now undergoing
restructuring, to arrange the deal between Taiheiyo and Mr Isutani. Sumitomo
Bank will also finance the joint venture in the acquisition.
The move comes as Mr Isutani plans to turn the Pebble Beach resort's four
golf courses and two hotels - originally accessible to the public  - into an
exclusive club by selling private memberships, were rejected by local
authorities.
The California Coastal Commission's refusal stalled Mr Isutani's plans to
repay his main lender, Mitsubishi Banking and Trust. Japan's faltering golf
membership market also discouraged Mr Isutani to pursue original plans.
Mr Isutani's original purchase stirred criticism in the US as it was seen as
another move by Japan to acquire high profile 'trophies' such as Manhattan's
Rockefeller Centre and Columbia Pictures.
Taiheiyo, which runs nine golf courses in Japan, said it hoped Pebble
Beach's name would help the company's reputation. Taiheiyo said it did not
intend to turn Pebble Beach into a private golf club, and said it would
retain original management. The company, which also hosts domestic golf
tournaments, hopes to finalise the deal before the US Open in June.
</TEXT>
