<HEADLINE>
FT  21 FEB 92 / UK Company News: Bensons pulled back by potato shortage
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Principally because of potato shortages last summer, Bensons Crisps saw
pre-tax profit fall from Pounds 1.36m to Pounds 1m in the year to November
30 1991.
Mr Malcolm Jones, chairman of this USM-quoted company, said the quality of
old crop potatoes in June was 'extremely poor' and there was a shortage of
new crop potatoes in July. The group ran up excess costs of Pounds 300,000
through higher prices paid for 'spot' potatoes, lower yields, factory
standing time and lost sales through limited production.
The pattern of forward purchases for 1992 has been changed to reduce the
risk of any recurrence, the chairman stated.
Sales rose to Pounds 26.3m (Pounds 22m). There was a significant switch in
consumer purchasing from standard packs to multipacks, with their inherent
lower margins. In addition, higher priced products suffered under consumer
down-trading.
Earnings came to 9.8p (12.5p). The final is held at 2.15p for a total of
2.85p (2.75p).
