<HEADLINE>
FT  21 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Court rules on poll tax computer
loophole
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE HIGH COURT yesterday refused to close the loophole holding up poll tax
prosecutions, ruling that liability orders based on computer print-outs were
illegal.
Declaring computer evidence 'hearsay', the court upheld an earlier ruling by
magistrates in Coventry. The ruling could affect thousands of pending
debt-collection cases.
The bill introducing the council tax, currently before the Lords, will make
such evidence admissible for the future, but councils are unlikely to
proceed with liability orders affected by the ruling until the bill becomes
law early next month.
Mr Michael Portillo, local government minister, said the bill had been
amended 'precisely to make clear that in future computer evidence will not
be regarded as hearsay'.
The Conservative-led Association of District Councils said the ruling was a
'disastrous setback to collection', which could jeopardise all liability
orders issued in the past three months.
</TEXT>
