<HEADLINE>
FT  21 FEB 92 / Cambodia may get 16,000 UN troops
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   UNITED NATIONS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE United Nations Secretary-General said yesterday a 15,900-member UN force
should be sent to Cambodia to keep the peace and help ensure a peaceful
transition to democracy after more than two decades of war, AP reports from
the United Nations.
Mr Boutros Boutros-Ghali recommended the UN dispatch 10,200 infantry troops,
an air support group of 326 members, a naval force of 376 with 20 boats, an
observer group of 485 members and other units to Cambodia.
In a report to the Security Council, the UN chief said 400 international
election monitors should also be sent to monitor polls scheduled for April
1993and that their number be augmented by 1,000 'international personnel.'
Mr Boutros-Ghali urged that 4,000 civilian officials be sent to register
voters, while UN military or police forces might be needed to provide
security at registration stations.
The proposed UN peacekeeping mission to Cambodia would be the biggest since
the world body deployed 20,000 peacekeepers to the Congo, now Zaire, in the
1960s.
</TEXT>
