<HEADLINE>
FT  21 FEB 92 / Ceasefire urged in Nagorno-Karabakh
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE foreign ministers of Armenia and Azerbaijan called on Thursday for a
ceasefire in the disputed territory of Nagorno-Karabakh, where four years of
fighting have claimed more than 1,000 lives, Reuter reports from Moscow.
The ministers said they would recommend a ceasefire to their presidents and
parliaments and urge steps to unblock roads, restore communications and
allow the urgent dispatch of humanitarian aid.
The move came as British officials said that the Conference on Security and
Cooperation in Europe (CSCE) was likely to make its first foray into
international mediation by offering to host talks on the war in
Nagorno-Karabakh.
A CSCE team which returned yesterday from the disputed territory was
expected to urge talks among all interested parties under the auspices of
the CSCE's Czechoslovak presidency.
If yesterday's accord in Moscow leads to a meaningful ceasefire CSCE
intervention may prove unnecessary. Mr Raffi Hovannisyan, foreign minister
of Armenia, and Mr Hussain Sadikhov, his Azeri counterpart, both called the
accord a first small step towards ending what Russian television this week
called the first war of the post-Soviet era.
They were speaking after eight hours of talks chaired by Russian Foreign
Minister Andrei Kozyrev. 'All participants of today's meeting were unanimous
that when there is war, when the guns are roaring, negotiations cannot
succeed,' Mr Sadikhov said.
'Therefore this recommendation was worked out to implement a ceasefire in
the zone of the Azeri-Armenian conflict.
'We do hope that in the near future we will see an end to the conflict, a
ceasefire, a lifting of blockades and respect for human and civil rights,'
Mr Hovannisyan said. The Armenian said he favoured the despatch of UN or
Commonwealth peace-keepers.
Itar-Tass news agency said Russian President Boris Yeltsin was holding
separate talks with Armenian President Levon Ter-Petrosyan in the Kremlin.
Mr Mikhail Gorbachev, then Soviet president, sent Soviet interior ministry
troops four years ago to restore order in Nagorno-Karabakh, an enclave ruled
by Azerbaijan since 1923 but populated mostly by ethnic Armenians.
The fighting has raged on despite mediation attempts by both Mr Gorbachev
and Mr Yeltsin, worsening sharply after the Soviet troops pulled out late
last year. Marshal Yevgeny Shaposhnikov, military commander of the new
Commonwealth of Independent States, this week proposed sending troops back
in.
</TEXT>
