<HEADLINE>
FT  20 FEB 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Broader market fails to
respond as Dow rises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US BLUE chips showed gains that the broader market was unable to register
yesterday as investors, encouraged by January economic data, bought
economically sensitive Dow constituent stocks, writes Karen Zagor in New
York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed 5.59 up at 3,230.32, after having
posted a modest loss in the first half-hour of trading. On the big board,
declining issues narrowly led advances by 950 to 756 after a fair New York
SE volume of 234.8m shares.
The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was just 0.88 firmer at 408.26, while secondary
stocks posted losses on the day, with the Nasdaq composite finishing down
4.00 at 622.41.
Hewlett-Packard, the computer company, jumped Dollars 9 1/8 to Dollars 73
1/2 after turning in first-quarter profits of Dollars 1.10 a share against
83 cents last year.
Rohr, an aircraft component manufacturer, dropped Dollars 2 to Dollars 18
1/8 . The company said it may face a federal indictment following a
government investigation of faulty testing which might bar it from winning
future government contracts.
Among active blue chip issues, AT&amp;T gained Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 38, Ford
Motor advanced Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 38 1/8 and General Motors rose
Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 38 3/8 .
News of reduced reserve requirements lifted some bank shares for a second
day. Citicorp added Dollars  1/4 at Dollars 16 3/4 and BancOne Dollars  7/8
at Dollars 47 3/4 .
Bank of Boston moved ahead Dollars 1 1/2 to a 52-week high of Dollars 17 7/8
after the stock was added to Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette's recommended
list.
News that Kroger, one of the largest US supermarket chains, plans to buy
back up to Dollars 100m of high-yield debt had little effect on the
company's stock, which eased Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 17 1/2 .
Biotechnology issues led the secondary market lower. Centocorp plunged
Dollars 8 1/8 to Dollars 33 1/8 in very heavy over-the-counter trading after
the company said that the US Food and Drug Administration had raised
questions about its important Centoxin drug to treat septic shock that might
delay the release of the drug and reduce 1992 earnings. Centocorp also
posted a fourth-quarter loss of Dollars 1.19 a share.
A series of disappointing corporate results also contributed to the
secondary market's slide. Fleer fell Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 22 1/2 on the
back of fourth-quarter earnings of 10 cents a share, compared with 27 cents
a year earlier. Analysts had expected earnings of about 30 cents in the
latest quarter.
Mail Box weakened Dollars 4 1/4 to Dollars 34 3/4 after turning in
third-quarter earnings of 30 cents a share, below earlier estimates of 35
cents a share but above the 24 cents reported the previous year.
Walt Disney declined Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 145 5/8 in spite of news that
its 'Beauty and the Beast' film had become the first animated film to be
nominated for the best picture category of the Academy Awards. The stock
gained Dollars 3 5/8 on Tuesday after the entertainment group announced
plans for a four-for-one stock split. Canada
THERE WERE moderate losses in most sectors yesterday, sending the Toronto
market lower for the seventh straight session. President George Bush's poor
showing in the New Hampshire primary added to the market's negative tone.
Analysts said the slim rise of only 0.1 per cent in the US consumer price
index for January eased fears of a resurgence in inflation, but had little
immediate effect on the market.
The composite index closed 7.9 easier at 3,543.3. Falls outscored rises by
350 to 230 after volume of 25.8m shares.
