<HEADLINE>
FT  20 FEB 92 / International Company News: Northrop advances at operating
level
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NORTHROP, the US defence contractor which is heavily dependant on the B-2
Stealth bomber programme, yesterday reported after-tax profits of Dollars
200.8m for 1991 - a little lower than the Dollars 210.4m seen in the
previous year.
However, comparisons between the two years are slightly misleading. The 1990
figure included a Dollars 67.1m after-tax gain from the sale of the
company's headquarters complex, while the 1991 results are depressed by
about Dollars 4m by accounting changes.
At the operating profit level, Los Angeles-based Northrop reported Dollars
474.2m, compared with Dollars 346.8m in the previous 12 months.
The company said profits were higher in the aircraft and the missiles and
unmanned vehicle systems divisions, but fell in the electronics business
segment, where the cost of settling legal and product disputes impinged.
Overall, sales for the year reached Dollars 5.69bn, up by 3.7 per cent on
1990.
In the fourth quarter alone, net profits improved from Dollars 42.7m to
Dollars 158.5m, with sales totalling Dollars 1.57bn (Dollars 1.52bn).
Northrop shares rose Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 25 7/8 yesterday.
</TEXT>
