<HEADLINE>
FT  20 FEB 92 / Greenspan sees early US recovery: Federal Reserve chairman
forecasts a return to lowest inflation level for a generation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Alan Greenspan, US Federal Reserve chairman, yesterday gave his most
upbeat congressional testimony since the summer, predicting an early
economic recovery and a fall in inflation to the lowest level for a
generation.
He said spending seemed to be rising in some sectors, and the decline in
industrial production in January did not appear to have carried over into
this month.
He acknowledged that the outlook was 'particularly uncertain' and warned
that recovery could 'peter out' as happened last year. However, he based his
prediction of a revival in business activity on structural changes under way
for the past two years.
Households and companies had made progress in repairing strained balance
sheets, he said. Banks and other lenders had begun to rebuild depleted
capital positions. Money supply was growing faster after a long period of
stagnation.
Mr Greenspan said the core rate of inflation was also falling rapidly,
forecasting that 'within the foreseeable future we will have attained the
lowest rates of inflation in a generation'.
Economic data released yesterday broadly supported his optimism. The annual
rate of consumer price inflation fell to 2.6 per cent in January. The
monthly increase in prices was only 0.1 per cent - less than financial
markets expected.
A separate report showed a 5.5 per cent jump in housing starts last month,
bigger than expected. The gain, however, was concentrated in only one region
 -the Midwest - and in the volatile apartment buildings sector.
Mr Greenspan was delivering testimony in support of the Fed's semi-annual
Humphrey-Hawkins monetary report to Congress. The report contains unchanged
target ranges for monetary growth. The target for M2, the main measure of
broad money, is 2.5 to 6.5 per cent. In recent years M2 growth has fallen
well below the mid-range of the Fed's targets, partly because of the
restructuring of banks and other financial institutions.
The report also predicts economic growth of 1 3/4 per cent to 2 1/2 per cent
during this year, roughly in line with the Bush administration's forecast of
2.2 per cent. It predicts inflation of 3 per cent to 3.5 per cent in the
year to the fourth quarter of 1992, with further progress in future years.
Mr Greenspan provided no clear signal on interest rates. However, his
bullish remarks about the economy may be interpreted as further evidence
that the Fed is not contemplating a further easing of monetary policy in the
near future.
He confirmed that the reduction in reserve requirements for commercial banks
announced on Tuesday was intended to boost bank profitability and ease the
credit crunch rather than as an easing of monetary policy.
Benefits of economy-wide restructuring, Page 6
</TEXT>
