<DOCNO>FT921-7775</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CBTB0AF7FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920220
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: 'Supergun' warnings given before
seizure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH intelligence received two separate warnings about the Iraqi
'supergun' project six months before British-made components for the gun
were seized, MPs heard yesterday.
Mr Stephan Kock, former non-executive director of the British defence group
Astra Holdings, told the Commons trade and industry committee that he had
notified the security services in September 1989.
He learned of contracts to supply propellants for the supergun during a
visit to PRB, the Belgian munitions company which Astra had recently
acquired. Mr Kock said he informed intelligence contacts by telephone on
September 22 and met them in London on October 11.
Mr Gerald James, then Astra's chairman, and Mr Christopher Gumbley, chief
executive, previously believed to have been the first to raise the alarm
about the supergun, were unaware of Mr Kock's actions. They met Ministry of
Defence officials, also believed to have links with the security services,
on October 26.
The MoD has written to the committee rejecting a request for the two
officials involved to give evidence, on the grounds that both have
'retired'.
A week after steel tubes intended to form part of the supergun were seized
at Teesport in April 1990 Mr Nicholas Ridley, then trade and industry
secretary, told parliament that the government only 'recently became aware
in general terms' of the Iraqi project.
Mr Kock was first named last year as a former consultant with Midland Bank's
secretive defence equipment financing department in a Financial Times
investigation which detailed links between some Midland executives and the
intelligence community.
While a career in the RAF, the special forces, and military intelligence in
Rhodesia had left him with extensive intelligence connections, Mr Kock said
yesterday that he had never worked as an MI6 officer.
He also denied any link between his work for Midland and his Astra role, and
allegations that he had known earlier of the PRB propellants orders and
visited Iraq to arrange financing by Midland.
He confirmed that he had fired a handgun into the air in an incident in 1990
near his home in Argyll. He denied, however, that his solicitor had said at
a subsequent court hearing that Mr Kock's defence work had left him with an
acute concern for his personal safety.
Earlier, Mr Christopher Gumbley talked publicly for the first time about a
meeting on March 22 1990 with Dr Gerald Bull, the Canadian scientist who
headed the supergun project, only hours before Dr Bull was shot by an
assassin.
Mr Gumbley, who had been arrested the previous week by Ministry of Defence
police on corruption charges, told MPs Dr Bull said he believed Mr Gumbley
was being 'set up' by the British government and PRB's former parent,
Societe Generale de Belgique, and offered to fund his defence.
'He said my arrest by the MoD police was an engineered manoeuvre, carried
out to discredit me and cause me to have to resign from Astra,' Mr Gumbley
said.
</TEXT>
