FT  20 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): Sale of skill centres condemned by
union
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A COMPANY that ceased trading soon after it took over four government
training centres was not fit to take over parts of the Civil Service, the
NUCPS Civil Service union told a cross-party committee of MPs yesterday.
In February 1990 the government paid Pounds 2.1m to TICC Skillcentres, which
took over four skill centres in Cumbria, East Lancashire, St Helens and
Ipswich. The company ceased trading in August last year. Only three of the
skill centres are likely to remain open, all with reduced provision.
Mr Tony Gallagher, NUCPS national officer, told the Commons employment
committee: 'We were concerned that TICC Skillcentres did not have a
background in training or any real knowledge of the sort of training that
skill centres deliver.
'We felt that they were characters that really were not worthy or fit people
to take over parts of the Civil Service.'
The union believes the government's choice of TICC was poor and said other
reputable companies had not been informed that the four skill centres were
available.
Mr Gallagher said TICC was headed by a Mr Lakin, whom he described as a
'Walter Mitty character' who claimed to have a friend at Deloitte Corporate
Finance, which handled the sale of the skill centres. Deloitte Corporate
Finance was part of Deloitte Haskins and Sells, the accountancy firm that
has since merged to become Coopers &amp; Lybrand Deloitte.
The union said that Mr Lakin went ahead with his bid after visiting the four
skill centres for an hour each over a weekend when none was open.
Union criticism of the sale surfaced after former civil servants were made
redundant when the skill centres went into liquidation last year.
It is understood that the government now feels the sale of the skill centres
to TICC was a mistake, but that at the time its vetting procedures passed
the company as suitable.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
