<HEADLINE>
FT  20 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Pressure seen from Commons business
 -Election timing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT will have no time to assess the impact of the Budget on
voters before it decides whether to opt for an April 9 election, the shadow
cabinet was told last night.
In a briefing paper on election timing, Mr Derek Foster, the Labour chief
whip, said that the tight schedule for Commons proceedings meant the
Opposition should refuse any backroom dealing to ease the pressure of
business on the government.
It was the weight of parliamentary business that meant Mr John Major, the
prime minister, would have only until the morning of March 12 - just two
days after the Budget - to make up his mind on whether to go to the polls on
April 9.
It was possible that the government would be forced to make MPs sit through
the weekend after the Budget to complete rushed business. Forcing MPs from
Tory marginals to stay in London was in Labour's interests, Mr Foster
concluded.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
