FT  20 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Poll tax default summonses reach
11m - News in brief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A TOTAL of about 11m summonses for poll tax non-payment were issued between
April 1 1990 and the end of last year, Mr John Patten, Home Office minister,
said yesterday, Alison Smith writes.
His written answer came after Mr David Blunkett, Labour's local government
spokesman, had highlighted the efforts of Labour councils to collect the
poll tax. In London's Lambeth and Islington more than 140,000 summonses had
been issued.
Mr Blunkett condemned the government for its delay in clearing up the
confusion about the admissibility of computer evidence in court and for
failing to abolish the minimum 20 per cent poll tax contribution by the
worst-off.
Mr Michael Portillo, local government minister, said the 10 councils with
the worst poll tax collection rates were all Labour-controlled.
*****
UNION ATTACK: Sir Patrick Mayhew, the attorney-general, yesterday joined the
Tory attack on Labour's links with unions by highlighting the party's
'sinister' plans to reform union law.
Sir Patrick said Labour's plans for a special industrial relations court
called into question its trust in the 'fairness' of the judiciary. He also
said some proposals were so loosely framed that they would allow a return to
the mass picketing of the 1970s.
*****
SUNDAY TRADING: A fresh attempt to break the deadlock on Sunday trading
reform was made yesterday in a backbench bill which would allow limited
types of shops to open but set stiffer penalties for those which break the
law.
The bill, to be debated tomorrow, has some cross-party support, but stands
no chance of becoming law.
</TEXT>
