<HEADLINE>
FT  20 FEB 92 / Move for broader auditing of results
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SENIOR ACCOUNTANTS are calling for companies' preliminary announcements,
which contain basic information on full-year results, to be scrutinised by
auditors.
The move comes after questions over the reliance placed by the financial
markets on figures which have not been verified by an external source.
A paper submitted to the auditing committee of the Institute of Chartered
Accountants in England and Wales argues that all quoted companies' auditors
should approve the preliminary announcements before they are released.
The case is likely to be submitted in the next few weeks to the Stock
Exchange, the Cadbury Committee on Corporate Governance and the Auditing
Practices Board, which sets guidelines for auditors.
Preliminary announcements, which are often issued several days or weeks
before the audited annual reports and accounts, very often have a
substantial effect on share prices. Publication of the report generally has
far less effect on the market.
The author of the report, Mr Graham Ward, vice-chairman of the committee and
a partner with Price Waterhouse, the accountancy firm, said: 'There is
something slightly anomalous when the primary document governing the
communication of results doesn't have particularly stringent rules governing
it.'
The Stock Exchange said there was little evidence of companies' preliminary
figures varying from those presented in the full accounts.
The accounting treatment of depreciation requires an overhaul to remove
inconsistencies, the Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales
said yesterday. It argues that any attempt to deal with depreciation by the
Accounting Standards Board, which drafts new standards, must first address
underlying conceptual problems.
A discussion paper prepared by the financial reporting committee of the
institute calls for clarification of the purpose and meaning of the balance
sheet; the definition and recognition of elements within financial
statements; and how these elements should be measured.
Accounting for Depreciation, ICAEW, Gloucester House, 399 Silbury Blvd,
Milton Keynes MK9 2HL. Free.
Accountancy Column, Page 15
</TEXT>
