<HEADLINE>
FT  20 FEB 92 / Rowntree charity calls for local income tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A LOCAL income tax to supplement council tax and give local government
greater autonomy was recommended yesterday by the Joseph Rowntree
Foundation, the charitable trust.
The report, by a team of former senior civil servants and local officials,
says a local income tax (LIT) would be 'by far the most suitable means of
restoring financial freedom to local authorities'.
The administrative requirements of such a tax could need some changes to
national income tax, the authors say.
The report - whose authors include Sir George Moseley, a former permanent
secretary at the Department of the Environment - suggests that local taxes
should cover about half of local revenue. 'The institution of LIT could be
accompanied by corresponding reductions in national taxes,' it says.
The report also says most other European countries have more than one type
of local tax.
The report deplores the 'climate of stress and mistrust' in relations
between central and local government, and recommends more interchange of
officials between the two levels.
Launching the paper, Sir Charles Carter, chairman of the foundation's
local-government committee, said: 'If good relations between local and
central government are to be restored, we need lasting solutions that
command support across the political divide'.
A New Accord, Rowntree Foundation, 40 Water End, York YO3 6LP, Pounds 7.50.
Editorial Comment, Page 20
