FT  20 FEB 92 / OFT urged to reopen Eurocopy inquiry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Nigel Griffiths, Labour spokesman on consumer affairs, yesterday called
on the Office of Fair Trading to reopen its inquiry into Eurocopy, the
photocopier distribution company which was cleared last month of allegations
that it was unsuitable to hold consumer-credit licences. An investigation
into the sales practices of some Eurocopy subsidiaries began last year.
Mr Griffiths said he had written to the OFT after receiving many complaints
about the copier group in the past 10 days. He was speaking at the launch of
the Campaign to Clean Up Copier Contracts, a lobby group set up to combat
what it sees as misleading contracts and selling practices in the
photocopier leasing industry.
Mr Michael Armitage, Eurocopy finance director, suggested that the OFT's
decision had, in effect, turned Eurocopy into a model for the industry. He
said the group had taken steps to reform its sales practices before the OFT
inquiry.
However, the OFT is believed to have written to Eurocopy saying that its
decision should not be seen in such a light, that several assurances about
future practices had been received from Eurocopy and that the company must
report to the OFT regularly the level of complaints it receives from
customers.
Mr Griffiths said the campaign would lobby for legislation to change the
Consumer Credit Act, which covers only agreements worth less than Pounds
15,000, and protects individuals rather than companies.
