<HEADLINE>
FT  20 FEB 92 / Car chief confident of Budget stimulus
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Geoffrey Whalen, chief executive of Peugeot Talbot, said yesterday he was
confident that next month's Budget would produce a 'significant' cut in the
10 per cent special car tax on new-car sales. He said the car market had
been 'artificially depressed' by high taxation.
Mr Whalen also called for a change in the balance of power between the
Department of Trade and Industry and the Treasury, with the DTI 'playing a
more powerful role in government and being consulted before the Treasury or
other departments adopt measures which might damage the interests of
manufacturing industry.'
Mr Whalen is the second motor-industry leader within two days to criticise
some aspects of the government's policies towards the motor industry.
On Monday, Mr George Simpson, Rover Group chairman, was severely critical of
the UK economy's volatility compared with its main rivals. He called for a
national industrial strategy - involving close consultation between
government and industry - along the lines of Germany or Japan.
However, Mr Whalen defended the government's overall record on reducing
inflation and dismissed as 'prophets of gloom' critics sceptical about the
industry's ability to recover.
Quality, productivity and industrial relations had all improved, 'and I am
convinced that when we are out of the current recession huge opportunities
will appear for those companies able to respond quickly and effectively', he
said.
Peugeot Talbot's productivity had risen 30 per cent since 1988, 'and we will
improve further'.
Most in the motor trade and industry believe that higher value added tax -
not reclaimable by companies on car purchases - and company car taxes
introduced in last year's Budget have played a significant role in the steep
decline in sales of new cars.
Like Mr Simpson, Mr Whalen emphasised his opposition to direct government
intervention in industry. 'There is a world of difference between a DTI
which is influential in creating the right operating environment for
industry and one which seeks to interfere in detail in the management of our
undertakings,' he said.
A survey by KPMG Peat Marwick, the accountancy firm, found that there could
be a substantial cut in the use of company cars by businesses if an
uncertainty involving VAT was resolved.
More than 90 per cent of the largest responding companies - those running
fleets of 500 cars or more - said they would offer a cash alternative to
company cars if fears of large VAT penalties on that cash sum were removed.
The survey drew responses from 335 companies operating between them more
than 90,000 cars.
</TEXT>
