<HEADLINE>
FT  20 FEB 92 / London health care seen as costly and flawed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HEALTH PROVISION in London is relatively expensive, but the capital's
residents are denied essential elements of an adequate service, according to
research published yesterday by the King's Fund health policy analysis
centre.
The findings will be taken into account by the government's inquiry into
London's health provision which began work in October. Future health care,
including whether all the London teaching hospitals should be kept, will be
one of the first politically sensitive health decisions for the next
government.
The King's Fund research concludes that London uses far more resources than
would be justified purely on population grounds. That is largely because of
a decline in the number of people living in the capital over the past 50
years.
The decline has been considerably offset by patients from outside districts
using the inner-London teaching hospitals. The fund says, however, that this
'pattern of provision of expensive services to non-residents is unlikely to
be sustainable in the long term'.
The King's Fund says that Pounds 2.9bn is spent on hospital and community
health services in London. That is 20 per cent of the English budget for
those services, although Londoners represent only 15 per cent of the
population.
However, it says that Londoners frequently experience problems in gaining
access to health care and there is evidence that specialist services have
developed at the expense of local ones.
During the 1980s plans were advanced to disperse some specialised medical
services away from the capital, but the report says that 'a further
expansion and concentration of most specialist services has taken place in
inner London between 1980 and 1990'.
The overall health of people living in London is found to be no worse than
those in other parts of the country, although poor health is strongly linked
to areas of deprivation in the city.
Kings Fund, 2 Palace Court, London W2 4HS. Telephone 071-727-0581.
Temperature rises, Page 21
</TEXT>
