<HEADLINE>
FT  20 FEB 92 / Parties agree on technology plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON, Science Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LABOUR and Conservative parties put forward similar proposals yesterday
to 'bridge the gap between academia and industry' by creating a national
network of technology development centres.
The government scheme was announced by Mr Kenneth Clarke, education
secretary, and Mr Peter Lilley, trade and industry secretary. They said that
it would start in the next academic year with a Pounds 2m pilot project
involving five partnerships between higher education institutions and
industrial research organisations.
Students would acquire degrees while working on industrial research.
The scheme would expand later into a network of 'centres of excellence in
particular technologies' - probably to be called Faraday Centres - which
would play a bridging role similar to the much-admired Fraunhofer Institutes
in Germany.
Labour's plan, announced by Mr Jeremy Bray, science spokesman, and Mr Lewis
Mooney, technology spokesman, calls for the creation of a national network
of Newton Institutes, each specialising in a branch of science or
engineering.
Although their proposed names honour different scientists, the Newton
Institutes and Faraday Centres seem virtually identical in conception. Both
are based on ideas from the Working Group on Innovation chaired by Sir John
Fairclough, chairman of the Centre for Exploitation of Science and
Technology in London.
Mr Neil Johnston of the centre said: 'It is encouraging that, whoever wins
the election, action will be taken to bridge the gap between higher
education and industry.'
Labour also proposed yesterday the creation of 'a new national focus for
science, in a permanent 'expo' of what science is today, how it is being
applied and where it is going'.
</TEXT>
