FT  20 FEB 92 / Injunctions sought over Lloyd's cash calls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONFRONTATION at Lloyd's of London, the insurance market, moved closer
yesterday as solicitors took legal action on behalf of hundreds of Names
facing financial ruin. A court hearing may take place as early as next week.
Mr Michael Freeman, a solicitor, issued motions for a number of injunctions
to prevent Lloyd's drawing down from the funds that Names - individuals
whose personal assets back underwriting - must deposit with agents when they
join the insurance market.
More than 600 Names are backing the action and the injunctions applied for
are designed to serve as test cases. Lloyd's has pledged to 'strongly
resist' them.
The Names are members of syndicates managed by Gooda Walker, Rose Thomson
Young, Feltrim and Devonshire that participated in 'spiral' reinsurance
business, in which syndicates reinsure each others' reinsurance exposures.
The injunctions are being sought on the grounds that cash calls by syndicate
managers are legally 'improper'.
Separately, more than 175 Names who were members of the syndicate 384
formerly managed by the Aragorn agency, met to press for compensation for
insurance losses.
The syndicate's losses from reinsurance business were nearly Pounds 11m.
Names want compensation for Pounds 6m of the losses which they allege were
brought about by the mistaken decision of Mr Graham Potter, 384's
underwriter, to underwrite 30.5 per cent of a risk when he had intended to
underwrite only 2.7 per cent.
In 1990 a Lloyd's disciplinary committee ordered Mr Potter to cease
underwriting at Lloyd's.
