<HEADLINE>
FT  20 FEB 92 / Food and drink sector leads rise of 0.4% in retail sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INCREASED food and drink sales led to a modest rise in high-street sales
last month, although the volume of sales in other sectors remained flat or
fell.
Figures released yesterday by the Central Statistical Office showed that
retail sales volumes in January rose by a seasonally adjusted 0.4 per cent
compared with December last year, following a 0.9 per cent monthly decline
in December. The latest figure gives a year-on-year increase of 0.9 per
cent.
But against a background of weak sales at the end of last year, and the
inability of any retail sector to sustain an upturn in sales, the latest
monthly improvement was greeted cautiously.
Food sales rose by 3.5 per cent on the month, but the volume of clothing and
footwear sales fell by 0.9 per cent and household goods sales, which had
improved in December, fell by 4.3 per cent.
'People should not read too much into the figures,' said Mr Gerard Lyons,
chief economist at DKB International, the Japanese-owned bank. 'If the
pick-up in household goods in December had continued into January, then I
think we could have become more confident about prospects for a recovery.'
The British Retail Consortium said the good performance of the food and
drink sector could be attributed to promotional prices during the month and
some benefit from Sunday trading.
Overall the volume of sales in the three months to January also rose 0.4 per
cent compared with the previous quarter.
Sales in November to January by food retailers rose 0.2 per cent, compared
with the previous three months, while sales by mixed-retail businesses fell
0.6 per cent. The sales of non-food retailers rose 1 per cent in the quarter
compared with the previous three-month period.
The latest slight improvement follows a report by the Confederation of
British Industry earlier this week indicating an increase in sales volumes
in the distribution industry.
Some economists believe lower mortgage rates - combined with rises in real
disposable incomes for those in employment over the past year - will help
spending recover this year.
However, stock-building figures also released yesterday showed continuing
gloom.
Stocks held by manufacturers, wholesalers and retailers fell by Pounds 969m
in the fourth quarter of last year compared with a Pounds 229m reduction in
the three months to September.
Manufacturers cut stocks by Pounds 767m following the previous quarter's
Pounds 145m reduction, while wholesalers' stocks were down Pounds 80m
compared with a previous quarterly fall of Pounds 167m. Retailers' stocks
fell Pounds 122m after an increase of Pounds 83m in the third quarter.
</TEXT>
