<HEADLINE>
FT  20 FEB 92 / Role of voluntary sector stressed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government yesterday published a plan to encourage the voluntary sector
to play an 'increasingly important part in society' in the 1990s, Alan Pike
writes.
In the plan, the government undertakes to establish an 'appropriate
framework for partnership' between the public sector, businesses and
voluntary organisations.
It is keen to encourage the voluntary sector to take over services and other
responsibilities traditionally provided by public authorities. Voluntary
organisations, however, are concerned that the government's enthusiasm for
the plan is not backed up by adequate financial support.
The Home Office says it would be 'unhealthy and damaging to its
independence' for the voluntary sector to depend too heavily on government
money. It sees the government's role as encouraging the development of a
climate favourable to support from other sources.
Among initiatives which the government says it will take to achieve this
climate will be a drive to encourage individuals to engage in voluntary
activity and become active in the community. It also intends to promote
improved management in the voluntary sector and identify ways of encouraging
employees to give more to charity through workplace-based payroll schemes.
The document says government departments will work in partnership with
businesses and voluntary organisations. Ministers will consider ways of
increasing the number of civil servants seconded to the voluntary sector.
Mr Kenneth Baker, home secretary, said the sector had a vital role. 'We have
a voluntary sector of a size, energy and range which is unique in Europe,
and the pace of change and development makes it one of the most dynamic and
exciting areas of activity within our national community.'
</TEXT>
