<HEADLINE>
FT  20 FEB 92 / Whitehall cool on EC 'green' plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT departments have expressed doubts about whether energy-saving
measures being proposed by Brussels will be sufficient to meet the European
Commission's objectives of reducing fuel consumption and lowering harmful
emissions.
Whitehall believes that the European Community would be wrong to go ahead
with its carbon-tax proposal unless other countries take similar action.
Instead, it calls for energy-conservation at a national level.
The UK's sceptical position is outlined in a joint report by the energy and
environment departments and the Treasury to the European Communities
committee of the House of Lords, which is holding hearings on energy today.
The report contains the first detailed assessment by the leading relevant UK
departments of EC energy and environmental measures. Although it stresses
that many of the EC proposals are still too vague to permit firm judgments
to be made, it underlines Whitehall's cautious approach to Brussels
initiatives.
The UK accepts that climate change poses a threat to the world, and will
require co-ordinated international action. But it argues that isolated
action by individual nations or regional groupings would not be effective in
combating harmful emissions.
Whitehall wants a framework convention that would commit all countries to
realistic and achievable strategies for limiting greenhouse gases.
The report also criticises the EC proposal to exempt energy-intensive
industries from the carbon tax in order to protect their international
competitiveness. It says that these exemptions would only create distortions
and throw the cost of adjustment on to energy consumers and other
industries.
The report also doubts whether the carbon tax could be 'neutralised', as
Brussels proposes, by redistributing the proceeds in the form of tax cuts or
benefits.
Britain's support for the carbon tax would be 'conditional on similar action
by other countries', the report says. It believes individual countries
should draw up their own programmes.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-7807</DOCNO>
