FT  20 FEB 92 / Lautro in first move to suspend a member
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LAUTRO, the self-regulating body for the life-assurance industry, has for
the first time suspended a member.
The action against Oaklife Assurance, based in Rickmansworth, Hertfordshire,
relates to its sales practices. The company has been ordered to stop selling
policies until the regulators are satisfied that Oaklife is able to comply
with the rules.
The company has 20 branches and sells policies through about 100 direct
sales agents. It has Pounds 800,000 of policies in force.
Lautro said Oaklife had breached a broad range of rules ranging from failure
to train staff properly to a failure to ensure that agents were urging
consumers to purchase the best possible policy for their needs.
Lautro recently announced a steep rise in complaints alleging sharp practice
by life-assurance sales agents to more than 4,000 in the 12 months to June
last year.
However, apart from cases where members have agreed or been ordered to make
restitution to customers, Lautro has rarely taken disciplinary action.
It has issued only four public reprimands to companies in the past two years
and has never expelled a member. In October the organisation's board
authorised it to fine members for breaches of rules relating to sales
practices but Lautro has yet to use those powers.
Last December the Department of Trade and Industry prohibited Oaklife from
selling policies for several weeks after the former chief executive and
three other top officials resigned, taking complaints about the company to
the DTI.
</TEXT>
