<HEADLINE>
FT  20 FEB 92 / US sends IRA man Doherty back to UK
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US yesterday sent Mr Joseph Doherty back to the UK, ending a nine-year
legal battle by the Irish Republican Army (IRA) member to escape
deportation.
Mr Doherty was convicted in 1981 of murdering a British army captain during
an ambush in Northern Ireland, but escaped from prison in Belfast before
being sentenced in his absence.
He was arrested in 1983 in New York, but the Justice Department's attempt to
extradite him to the UK as a convicted criminal failed when a federal judge
ruled that his crime was a political offence.
Mr Doherty, who entered the US under an assumed name in 1982, at first
agreed to be deported to Ireland as an illegal alien.
After the UK signed an extradition treaty with the Republic of Ireland in
1987, however, he asked to have his deportation case reopened and requested
political asylum.
This battle ended when the Supreme Court ruled in December that Mr Doherty
was not entitled to a new asylum hearing.
American supporters of the IRA have fought hard for Mr Doherty, whose case
won the backing of more than 100 members of Congress, as well as Mayor David
Dinkins and Cardinal John O'Connor of New York.
Mr Doherty was flown to the UK by the US Air Force yesterday and was
expected to reach his Belfast prison late last night.
</TEXT>
